From: vaughanj@itdsrv1.ul.ie (Joe Vaughan)
Subject: Memory management and swapping problems......
Date: Fri, 22 Oct 1993 13:10:35 GMT

Help!!!!!

Setup : SLS 1.02 Distribution of Linux 99pl9 on 
        Dan Technologies 486DX66/2
        4Mb RAM
        CL54?? (Cant remember!!! Not important) 1Mb SVGA Card
        XGA Monitor.

Ok.... 

My problem is this.... Linux absolutely chews the RAM memory down to 40k
and then starts swapping..... however thats well and good but anything more 
intensive than 'ls' locks the machine proper......

Now... we've upgraded to 8Mb .. much better but still it chews up the RAM
to that 40k mark.... this from the OS with the 4Mb Max-overhead.... 

So it seems... the more memory I stick in... the more it'll chew.... (standard
UN*X trait anyway).... but then what do I about my X... :((((

Also.... the memory management seems to be very dirty... with some programs
leaving their footprints in memory long after termination and the kernel not
tidying up...... (Mind you... the X server is great at doing this.... hence 
my current kludge when I'm really stuck is to startup X and then quit X)

The question is this.... any way to make linux 
a) Tidy up memory better 
b) make sure there is alway 1Mb free RAM.
c) anything that'll allow me to tell the kernel to swap out a chunk of memory
   on command......

Anyone got any suggestions ???


All answers on a postcard to vaughanj@itdsrv1.ul.ie :)))

JoeV.

-- 
JoeV

Joe Vaughan.            | "Yet not the more cease I to wander where the muses
University of Limerick, |  haunt, Cleer Spring or Shadie Grove or Sunnie Hill,

